 Liveness Probe Failures

Your application starts successfully.

The pod enters the Running state.

But after a few minutes, Kubernetes starts restarting the container repeatedly.

❌ Restart Loop

❌ Frequent Container Restarts

❌ Application Instability

In many cases, the root cause is a Liveness Probe Failure.

Recently, I encountered an application that was running correctly, but Kubernetes continuously restarted the container because the liveness probe kept failing.

🔍 My troubleshooting approach:

✅ Checked pod restart count

✅ Reviewed pod events

✅ Examined liveness probe configuration

✅ Verified application health endpoint

✅ Tested endpoint response time

✅ Checked resource utilization

✅ Analyzed application logs

✅ Reviewed startup and processing times

🎯 Root Cause:

The liveness probe timeout was configured too aggressively.

During heavy processing, the application took longer than expected to respond to health checks.

Kubernetes interpreted the delayed response as a failure and restarted the container repeatedly.

After tuning the probe parameters and increasing timeout values, the application remained stable and restart loops stopped.

💡 Key Takeaway:

When troubleshooting Liveness Probe Failures, remember that liveness probes determine whether a container should be restarted.

Always verify:

• Health check endpoint

• timeoutSeconds

• periodSeconds

• failureThreshold

• Application response time

• CPU and memory utilization

• Application logs

Useful commands:

kubectl describe pod <pod-name>

kubectl logs <pod-name>

kubectl get pod <pod-name> -o wide

Remember:

📌 Readiness Probe = Can traffic be sent?

📌 Liveness Probe = Should the container stay alive?

📌 Poorly configured liveness probes can create unnecessary restart loops.

Every troubleshooting session helps us better understand application behavior and Kubernetes self-healing mechanisms.
